<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JAN 92 / The Lex Column: British Gas
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Yesterday's initial 4 per cent jump in British Gas shares on its
capitulation to the Office of Fair Trading showed how little faith the
market had in the gasman's willingness to bow to the inevitable. The fact
that the gain then all but evaporated was a more realistic measure of the
difficulties Gas faces. Having claimed that its ability to meet shareholder
expectations on dividends would be hampered unless its regulator also
climbed down, Gas can do little more than put on a brave face while it is
broken into pieces.
The shares will increasingly suffer a two-way pull, with their yield
attraction diminishing as their break-up value is clarified. The message
will doubtless not be lost on investors in BT. As Sir Bryan Carsberg
prepares to leave Oftel, his counterpart at Ofgas has shown what a
determined regulator can achieve. A new incumbent at Oftel might choose to
take up the challenge: a new government might conceivably require it.
</TEXT>
