<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Row over EC regional commissione
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE political impartiality of Mr Bruce Millan, the EC Commissioner for
regional policy, was questioned by Mr Edward Leigh, junior trade and
industry minister, in the Commons yesterday, Ivor Owen writes.
He accused Mr Millan, a former Labour cabinet minister, of holding back
Pounds 109m in EC funds intended to benefit coalfield communities in
Britain.
The minister claimed that while Mr Millan was dissatisfied with the
accountancy procedures of Italy, the Netherlands and France in respect of EC
funds, he had chosen to withhold only grants due to Britain because of
arrangements designed to ensure that the level of public expenditure was
determined at Westminster and not in Brussels.
Mr Tam Dalyell (Lab Linlithgow) attacked Mr Leigh for a 'slur' on Mr Millan,
and recalled that a leaked draft letter disclosed that Mr Michael Heseltine,
environment secretary, had argued that the government's arrangements for
dealing with the EC funds were 'no longer tenable'.
OIL REVENUES: The Treasury has gained Pounds 72bn from North Sea oil
revenues since 1969-70, or Pounds 112bn at today's prices, Mr John Maples,
economic secretary to the Treasury, said in a Commons written reply
yesterday.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 12
