<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JAN 92 / Study shows effects of inward investment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE KNOCK-ON effects of foreign direct investment to the UK are numerous,
widespread and not always transparent, according to a study commissioned by
the Department of Trade and Industry.
The study, carried out by Coopers &amp; Lybrand Deloitte in collaboration with
Benchmark Research, was prompted by the growing significance of inward
investment to the economy. It says inward investment might account for as
much as 25 per cent of all new capital formation in 1991-92, against 15 per
cent in 1989.
There have been numerous studies into the direct impact of inward
investment, but the latest report aims to analyse less tangible effects on
local economies and communities within the English regions.
The study says the primary beneficiaries of inward investment are groups
that have established a direct relationship with the inward investor -
employees, local component suppliers, local service companies and local
customers.
The less tangible effects, such as involvement with local charities or links
with educational establishments, indicate the degree of integration into the
local economy.
While only a sixth of the companies examined were actively collaborating or
planning to collaborate in research and development with another company,
almost half were working on R&amp;D with one or more academic institution,
nearly all of which were local.
Japanese companies led the field in collaborating with academic
institutions, and the high incidence of collaboration by mechanical
engineering companies had brough significant local benefits through
technology transfer.
In general inward investment is considered to be 'a good thing', not only by
the investors but by most other companies and organisations within each
region.
</TEXT>
