FT  16 JAN 92 / Olszewski battles to curb deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER BOBINSKI
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WARSAW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
POLAND'S economic situation was much worse than he expected before taking
office Mr Jan Olszewski, the Polish prime minister, told the Senate
yesterday. Appealing to parliament's upper chamber to pass the government's
first quarter budget provisions, the newly appointed head of government
added: 'Maybe I wouldn't have taken on this responsibility if I had known
what I know now.'
Speaking on the eve of a threatened one-day protest strike by members of the
former communist trade unions, Mr Olszewski warned that even after cuts in
government spending aimed at reducing the budget deficit target to Zl
17,600bn (Pounds 890m) the real budget out-turn could be overwhelmed by the
volume of overdue 1991 payments. These could add another Zl 20,000bn to the
total, he said.
In an attempt to bring the deficit under control the government has cut
energy subsidies and reduced unemployment pay, setting off a wave of labour
unrest.
Preliminary figures issued by the Central Statistical Office, however, show
the depth of a recession which has cut industrial production in the state
sector by nearly 40 per cent over the last 2 years and seen unemployment
rise from practically zero in 1989 to 2.1m, or 11.4 per cent of the work
force last month.
Year on year inflation, however, fell to 60.4 per cent in December from 249
per cent in December 1990 while real incomes grew by 3.1 per cent after a 25
per cent decline in 1990.
