<HEADLINE>
FT  16 JAN 92 / Secret talks reopened on Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZAGREB
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE governments of Serbia and Croatia have revived secret negotiations aimed
at dividing up the ethnically-mixed republic of Bosnia-Hercegovina, Bosnian
officials said yesterday. They warned that any such attempt would lead to
terrible bloodshed.
Mr Haric Silajcic, Bosnia-Hercegovina's foreign minister, said Mr Nikolai
Koljevic, a prominent member of Bosnia's Serbian Democratic Party, had held
informal talks with President Franjo Tudjman of Croatia in Zagreb on
Tuesday.
'The two extreme wings of Croats and Serbs in Bosnia, which are supported by
Mr Tudjman and Mr Slobodan Milosevic (Serbia's president) respectively, are
trying to carve up our republic,' explained Mr Silajcic.
Mr Rusmir Mahmutcehajic, Bosnia's deputy prime minister, said Mr Tudjman
wanted to revive the districts of 1939 when Croatia included parts of
western Hercegovina. Croatian academics believe Mr Tudjman wants to bring
Croats together in one independent state, as Mr Milosevic wants to do with
the Serbs.
Any agreed break-up between Zagreb and Belgrade would give Serbia the
opportunity to link the self-proclaimed Serb-inhabited republic of Krajina,
in south-western Croatia, with Serbia by driving a wedge across
north-western Bosnia.
Both ministers said the negotiations, first started between the two
presidents in March 1991, had been revived to try to shore up the flagging
support of the Croat and Serb presidents. Nationalists on both sides have
become disillusioned because Serbia has failed to quash Croatia's
independence bid, while a third of Croatia's territory is still under the
control of Serb militants and the army.
Bosnia-Hercegovina's 4.3m population is divided between Moslems (44 per
cent), Serbs (33 per cent) and Croats (17 per cent). The militant Serbs, led
by Mr Radovan Karadzic, a Milosevic ally, could rely on the army in the
event of a forcible break-up of the republic.
The army, which has put more soldiers into Bosnia-Hercegovina as it
partially withdraws from neighbouring Croatia, is under the control of
General Vladimir Vukovic, a Serb nationalist closely connected with General
Blagoje Adzic, the new defence minister, and Mr Milosevic.
Mr Alija Izetbegovic, the republic's president, flew yesterday to Paris with
Mr Silajcic for urgent talks with President Francois Mitterrand on Bosnia's
internal problems. Before leaving, he said: 'Some of our politicians are so
short-sighted that they cannot see that nobody can partition the republic
and not even a single village can be taken from it.'
However, Mr Stjepan Kljuic, the moderate head of Bosnia's Croatian
Democratic Union party, the sister party of Mr Tudjman's party in Croatia,
is losing ground to Mr Marte Boban, the Croat nationalist leader in western
Hercegovina.
On the other side, prominent Croat intellectuals from Sarajevo, the Bosnian
capital and opposition parties in Croatia and Serbia have protested against
any attempt to carve up the republic.
</TEXT>
