</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SETTLEMENT has been reached between the US Internal Revenue Service and
Executive Life of California (ELIC), the ailing Los Angeles-based insurer,
the Californian Insurance Department announced yesterday, writes Nikki Tait.
A Dollars 643m tax claim against ELIC had threatened to jeopardise attempts
to rehabilitate the life insurer, which was seized by state insurance
regulators in April after a policyholder run. Yesterday, however, the
insurance department said that the claim had been settled for Dollars 73m.
Late last year, the insurance department struck a deal with a French
consortium, led by Credit Lyonnais and its Altus Finance subsidiary, over
ELIC's future. Essentially, Altus would acquire ELIC's junk bond portfolio,
while a group of French investors would take over the restructured insurance
liabilities.
Since then, two major matters - the tax claim and a dispute over how holders
of ELIC's municipal guaranteed investment contracts should be treated in
this reorganisation - have required resolution.
