<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 92 / International Company News: Motorola climbs to Dollars 126m
as sales rise by 4%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MOTOROLA, the leading US electronics and semi-conductor manufacturer,
reported improved fourth-quarter results, buoyed by the performances of its
semi-conductor, cellular telephone and paging businesses.
Fourth-quarter income rose to Dollars 126m, or 96 cents a share, from
Dollars 109m, or 82 cents, in the fourth quarter of 1990, when Motorola
suffered an earnings decline. Sales for the quarter rose 4 per cent to
Dollars 3.04bn from Dollars 2.93bn in the same period last year.
Fourth-quarter results reflected 'sluggish economies in the US and Europe',
Mr George Fisher, chairman and chief executive, said.
'This impact should continue to be felt in the first half of 1992 with the
potential for modest economic growth in the second half.'
Sales for the full year increased 4 per cent to Dollars 11.34bn, from
Dollars 10.88bn in 1980. However, earnings declined to Dollars 454m, or
Dollars 3.44 per share, from Dollars 499m, or Dollars 3.80, in the previous
year.
Motorola said sales of its communications products rose two per cent in
1991, against the previous year. Semi-conductor products sales rose 7 per
cent. However, the company's computer sales fell 2 per cent and the
information products group recorded increased operating losses for the year.
The company also recorded losses due to investments in a proposed global
communications system called Iridium.
Military and government sales fell 8 per cent, despite a significant
contract for secure telecommunications equipment from Saudi Arabia. The
Automotive and Industrial Electronics group reported an 8 per cent increase
in sales.
