FT  15 JAN 92 / UK Company News: Barbour Index rides the recession with 5%
rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GRAHAM DELLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE recession in the construction industry has failed to dent profits growth
at Barbour Index, the specialist information supplier.
On turnover ahead from Pounds 6.94m to Pounds 7.17m, the pre-tax line for
the half year to end-October rose some 5 per cent to Pounds 2.78m (Pounds
2.66m). The shares rose 12p to 191p.
'The recession is still with us, it just means we have to work a lot harder
and be a good deal smarter' said Mr Jack Dunn, appointed chief executive in
a revamped management structure.
This has seen the group split from two to four operating divisions: the
renowned and weighty compendium - 'you could build buildings with it' Mr
Dunn said - used as a reference manual by the construction industry; the
telephone enquiry service, the microfile, used by quantity surveyors and
architects; and the health and safety division, which was doing 'bloody
well' according to Mr Dunn.
The interim dividend goes up from 2.2p to 2.4p, payable from earnings of
11.1p (10.5p) per share.
