FT  15 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Greater employee say urged by
pensions body - Social Security committee
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYEES should be given equal representation on pension fund boards of
trustees in order to prevent the repetition of a 'Maxwell-like scandal', the
National Association of Pension funds said yesterday.
In testimony to the Commons social security committee, Mr Brian McMahon,
NAPF chairman, said employers and employees should have equal representation
with independent trustees appointed in appropriate situations.
'Care should be taken to avoid domination by any one party,' the NAPF said.
The NAPF is the leading industry group on pensions in the UK and its members
run pension schemes with more than Pounds 250bn in assets.
The committee, which on Monday sought to question Mr Kevin and Mr Ian
Maxwell about the Maxwell company pension funds, is considering proposing
reforms to UK pensions law.
The NAPF also urged that assets of pension funds should be held by a
custodian trustee independent of the employing company. It added that where
investment management is carried out internally, as it was for much of the
Mirror Group Pension fund, the Investment Management Regulatory Organisation
(Imro) set tougher rules. Mr McMahon said the disappearance of Maxwell
pension funds assets reflects weaknesses in the regulation of fund managers
rather than of pension funds.
'The supervision of an investment manager entrusted with the Mirror Group
pension funds was inadequate,' Mr McMahon said. 'We should like to see the
Financial Services Act amended to five protection to members of pension
schemes.'
The NAPF also urged that the 5 per cent limit on self-investment be applied
to all types of investments, and said that a two to five-year period would
be sufficient to wind down portfolios that currently exceed that limit.
</TEXT>
