<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: PM fails to defuse BR privatisation
row - Transport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and RICHARD TOMKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR failed yesterday to resolve the potentially damaging cabinet
clash over privatisation of British Rail which threatens to delay yet again
the publication of government plans for the sale.
After a lengthy meeting in Downing Street chaired by the prime minister,
officials said ministers were 'a long way off' deciding between the three
options that Whitehall departments are promoting.
The row, if not resolved quickly, might embarrass Mr Major deeply in the
approach to the general election, when British Rail privatisation is set to
be a central part of the Conservative manifesto.
Publication of a white paper setting out details of how BR is will be sold
has already been delayed twice. The Citizen's Charter promised a white paper
by the end of last year. Ministers then promised publication for this week.
Downing Street said only that a white paper would be published before the
general election - in spite of Department of Transport promises of
publication in February at the latest.
The Department of Transport has now changed its stance again, saying the top
priority of Mr Malcolm Rifkind, transport secretary, was to get the right
solution, not a rushed one. 'We can't rule in or out any timings at this
stage,' officials said.
Mr Rifkind is understood to be putting up a determined fight to defend his
department's proposals, but he appears to be losing ground to a rival scheme
proposed by the prime minister's policy unit.
The Department of Transport wants to sell off BR's profitable InterCity and
freight services but keep regional rail networks in the public sector,
although they could eventually transfer to private operators.
However, under the scheme prefered by Mr Major, BR would be split into
regional companies similar to the set up before the Second World War - the
so-called 'golden age' scenario.
Meanwhile, Mr Peter Lilley, trade and industry secretary, has proposed a
scheme for privatisation which he believes would promoted maximum
competition. British Rail's track would be sold to a private operator with
private-sector companies competing to provide services.
Downing Street was sceptical of a compromise, pointing out that the schemes
were not easily compatible.
Mr Major told MPs yesterday that the government's aim was to ensure
passengers got better services.
The Department of Trade and Industry argues that the government should learn
from the experience of past privatisations and not simply create private
sector monopolies.
</TEXT>
