<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 92 / The small business small business
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S first baby hotel opened in London yesterday promising its guests
'a complete haven' away from the lifestyles of their busy parents.
Pippa Pop-ins, based in a customised four-storey Georgian house, caters for
children aged from two to 12 years old whose parents want a break from their
offspring for up to three days.
Cuisine tends more towards home cooking than cordon bleu and all but the
shyest guests will share bedrooms.
At Pounds 25 per weekday night per child and Pounds 30 a night during the
weekend, the overnight nursery is at the cheaper end of the London
accommodation market but the steeper end of the babysitting market.
Managing director Ms Pippa Deakin and her father, Tim, put up Pounds 20,000
themselves and have a Pounds 120,000 bank loan.
The Fulham Road premises are rented by the company and refurbishment cost
substantially more than Pounds 50,000.
Legal safety and security requirements have pushed up costs.
The directors do not expect to see a return on their money for five years,
assuming the nursery works at full capacity (21 children at the day nursery
and 12 overnight).
Ms Deakin, 26, has spent the last 10 years working with children. She took
business advice from Mr Nick Wilcockson, a Salomon Brothers stockbroker, who
is the company's financial director.
Limited publicity in June brought the nursery over 300 inquiries from
parents. Most tend to be professionals and some are single parents.
Diplomats and tourists have also expressed interest.
If the business is successful, the directors say they may consider
franchising their product. They say they have already had inquiries from
Switzerland, Italy and the US.
</TEXT>
