<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 92 / Hopes for housing rescue rent asunder: Why the government
emergency plan has made little progress
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANY homeowners with mortgage arrears saw the government's mortgage-rescue
scheme as a welcome Christmas present.
Yet, almost a month after the scheme was announced, there has been little
progress in implementing it. Most lenders seem to have done little to ease
up on repossessions. Lenders and housing associations have yet to agree
terms for the mortgage-to-rent schemes at the centre of the plan.
High-level negotiations on how to structure mortgage-to-rent schemes are
under way between the Council of Mortgage Lenders (CML), the National
Federation of Housing Associations (NFHA) and the Housing Corporation, which
regulates associations receiving public money.
But Mr Stuart Bernau, general manager at Nationwide Building Society, told a
meeting of housing association executives on Monday that the number of
detailed negotiations between individual lenders and associations was 'very
small indeed'.
Mr Stephen Duckworth, head of housing finance at the NFHA, told the meeting
that there were many difficulties to be resolved if mortgage-to-rent schemes
were to be agreed. They include:
The interest rates that lenders will charge associations on loans to buy
repossessed homes. The basis of valuations of such homes. Mortgage arrears.
The associations want lenders to write off some or all of existing arrears
to make it easier for their new tenants to meet rental payments.
Costs incurred on legal advice, surveys and valuations, administration and
chasing bad debts should be paid by lenders, the associations say.
The lenders see associations piling up demands that are tantamount to a
'scroungers' charter'. Mr Bernau told Monday's meeting there would be no
incentive for owners to keep up mortgage payments if default meant lower
monthly outgoings in rent, their debts written off and their property
upgraded.
The associations' demands are opening bids in negotiations that have much
further to go before what one executive described as a 'chasm' between the
two sides is bridged. Some of the larger building societies, such as
Nationwide and Woolwich, say that negotiations over terms are well advanced
with individual associations.
Mr Tim Melville-Ross, chief executive of Nationwide, hopes to reach
agreement on a mortgage-to-rent scheme by the end of the month. 'It is
important to get a pilot scheme going to avoid a massive loss of credibility
for the whole exercise.'
Until workable mortgage-to-rent schemes are agreed, lenders will be
unwilling to change their repossession policies. As a result, help for
homeowners in arrears may be some time in coming.
</TEXT>
