<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 92 / Nedo chief warns on devaluation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SENIOR UK official warned yesterday that a devaluation of sterling would
put Britain back in the European Community's 'third division' in terms of
inflation and would lead to a further rise in interest rates.
Mr Walter Eltis, director-general of the National Economic Development
Office, said that reducing sterling's value or trying to force down interest
rates would do nothing to alter the underlying challenge facing the UK
economy, which was to ensure that industry adopted Japanese-style best
practices in management.
He told a conference on the economy organised by the Institute of Economic
Affairs, the free-market think tank, that Britain needed another nine-year
period of expansion, like the one experienced in the 1980s, which would
allow further industrial restructuring.
The motor industry had been successfully restructured since the mid-1980s
with Japanese capital and working methods, and a new period of sustained
expansion could allow other sectors to follow that example.
It was more important to create the right conditions for such a sustained
expansion than to worry about the timing of the recovery, Mr Eltis said.
Other speakers at the conference were more concerned about the weakness of
the economy. Mr Peter Warburton, chief economist of Robert Fleming
Securities, became the first City economist to fore-cast zero growth this
year.
He urged the immediate floating of sterling and a cut of 2 percentage points
in interest rates to restore activity and stop job losses. Mr Warburton said
that uncertainty over the result of the general election was postponing
economic decisions. Moreover, the economy was in unknown territory because
of the unpredictability of the response of consumers and busines to the
accumulation of debt.
Mr Giles Keating, chief economist of Credit Suisse First Boston in London,
gave a warning that recovery might be hindered by weakness of the banking
sector, and urged a substantial cut in bank base rates this year.
Mr Keating said political uncertainty was adding to the linked difficulties
of the pound and high interest rates.
He added that Britain needed an election as soon as possible to overcome the
troubles of the economy and the banking sector.
</TEXT>
