<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Mediation urged to avoid 'overcrowded'
courts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT was urged yesterday to back the private resolution of
disputes as an alternative to the 'inefficient and overcrowded' public
courts system.
The Adam Smith Institute, a rightwing think tank, said private alternative
dispute resolution (ADR), through mediation or mini-trials conducted by
trained mediators or retired judges and lawyers, should be recommended by
the government.
The institute said the evidence against ADR from the US, where it had been
used for many years, was largely anecdotal and sensationalised.
Critics attempted to cast ADR in the worst possible light - referring to it
as 'Cadillac justice' apparently favouring those who could afford to pay for
it - or implied that it would create a two-tier system.
The institute said the arguments against ADR were easily outweighed by the
benefits of speedy, efficient and cost-effective solutions with the added
benefit of preserving the business relationship between parties to
commercial disputes.
It urged the government to avoid allegations of creating a system available
only to the rich by extending legal aid to cover individuals who wanted to
opt for ADR.
The institute said public courts should take steps to introduce ADR
procedures. 'An increase in the number of options available to disputants
who do seek to remain within the public courts could only add to the
credibility of the traditional system of dispute resolution.'
Judgement Day, by Adam Thierer. ASI, 23 Great Smith St, London SW1. Pounds
17.00.
</TEXT>
