<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 92 / Argentina beats IMF targets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN BARHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUENOS AIRES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ARGENTINA has bettered stringent economic targets set by the International
Monetary Fund for the final quarter of last year, opening the way for fresh
loans from the IMF and other lenders this spring.
Officials reported yesterday the government had a Dollars 1.74bn (Pounds
970m) budget surplus in the final quarter of 1991, against a Fund target of
Dollars 1.43bn.
Earlier, independent economists had cast doubts on the government's ability
to meet the surplus without including windfalls from larger than expected
privatisation receipts or by delaying payments. In the previous quarter the
budget surplus was only Dollars 989m.
The budget operating surplus, which excludes privatisation receipts, rose by
206 per cent over the third quarter to Dollars 1.1bn. Privatisation revenues
of Dollars 635m were hardly changed.
However, the surplus was only attained by a one-off inflow from a tax
amnesty and by deferring Dollars 360m-Dollars 380m in public sector
Christmas bonuses to January.
The improved budget figures will strengthen the position of Argentine
officials now in the US negotiating with the IMF and commercial banks.
Argentina wants to convert the Dollars 1.04bn standby loan it obtained from
the IMF last July to a Dollars 3bn, three-year extended fund facility loan.
This would unlock other loans from the Inter-American Development Bank, the
World Bank and - officials hope  - from the Japanese government.
The loans would help finance a reduction in Argentina's Dollars 35bn foreign
bank debt under the aegis of the Brady debt reduction scheme. Argentine
officials are holding preliminary talks with bank executives in New York on
refinancing more than Dollars 8bn in interest arrears before discussing
reduction of the bank debt.
The budget figures are coming under intense scrutiny because they are a key
to economic stability.
</TEXT>
