<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 92 / MCC chiefs signed cash transfers: Price Waterhouse suspects
Pounds 339m from company was used to prop up shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIGNATURES of three executives of Maxwell Communication Corporation, as well
as those of Mr Robert Maxwell and his sons, were on documents authorising
the transfer of Pounds 339m from MCC which investigators suspect was used
for an illegal share support operation.
Startling new evidence contained in a confidential report by accountants
Price Waterhouse shows that between April and July last year transfers to Mr
Maxwell's private companies stripped MCC of all liquid assets, giving its
head office bank account a Pounds 105m overdraft, on top of its other debts
of Pounds 1.6bn.
Although there was nothing illegal in the transfer of these funds, Mr David
Lee of Price Waterhouse said yesterday: 'It is a coincidence too great to be
overlooked that MCC's money flowed out in mid-1991 at the same time as its
shares rocketed - some of these large payments were probably used to support
its own shares.'
Between March and June 1991 the MCC share price surged from 150p to 240p.
The report, codenamed Project Lucy, calculates that Mr Maxwell would have
needed to spend about Pounds 300m to take his private shareholding in MCC
from 51 per cent in mid-1990 to 79 per cent at his death on November 5.
All the MCC shares owned by Mr Maxwell were eventually pledged to bank
creditors of his private companies as security. These shares are now
regarded as worthless by the banks, which face losses of many millions of
pounds.
The alleged share support scheme, which used secret foundations to buy MCC
shares, is the subject of one of five investigations by the Serious Fraud
Office. It is an offence under UK company law for a company to purchase its
own shares without shareholders' approval.
Mr Albert Fuller, head of MCC's treasury or funding operations, is a central
figure in the transfer of funds, according to the Price Waterhouse report,
delivered to the banks on December 18. His signature appears on Pounds 33m
of payments between April 29 and July 22.
There is no evidence to suggest that Mr Fuller and other MCC directors -
apart from Mr Robert Maxwell - knew the reason for the transfers. Mr Robert
Maxwell's signature is on Pounds 241m worth of them.
The report also shows the powers that Mr Robert Maxwell won from the company
in 1981 which gave him the right to make payments without other directors'
assent. Authorisation of payments otherwise needed two signatures.
On November 26 1981, after Mr Maxwell rescued the company, then called
British Printing Corporation, from financial disaster, a resolution was
passed 'that the chairman . . . is hereby appointed a committee of the board
and that there be . . . delegated to the chairman as such commit-tee all the
powers of the board'. The powers were never rescinded.
According to the Price Waterhouse investigation, Mr Maxwell's youngest son,
Kevin, MCC's chief executive, signed Pounds 52m of transfers and his brother
Ian Pounds 8m. Mr Jean Pierre Anselmini, the former deputy chairman, signed
only Pounds 2m and Mr Basil Brookes, finance director, only Pounds 1m, even
though their positions suggested they had a central role in the company's
finance.
MCC directors have said they protested to Mr Robert Maxwell about the
transfers and after they took independent legal advice in August money began
flowing back to MCC.
Price Waterhouse said yesterday that transfers were later authorised -
Pounds 2.5m on September 13 by the signatures of Mr Brookes and Mr Fuller,
and Pounds 14.7m on September 20 by the signatures of Mr Brookes and Mr
Kevin Maxwell. They added that their report was based on documents at MCC,
where they have been appointed administrators under UK insolvency law. They
are now checking that the signatures authorising the transfers are
authentic.
Mr Kevin Maxwell was in court yesterday for the second day of his appeal
against the high court's decision that he must answer questions from
Bishopsgate Investment Management about missing pension funds.
