<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 92 / Major fuels forecasts of tax-cutting Budget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR yesterday fuelled intense speculation at Westminster that the
government is preparing a tax-cutting Budget as the platform for its general
election campaign.
His comments in the House of Commons came amid indications that new tax
allowances for working mothers and further incentives to encourage saving
might accompany a reduction in income tax if Mr Norman Lamont, the
chancellor, can find sufficient room for manoeuvre.
They coincided also with indications from a new opinion poll that the
Conservatives' onslaught early last week on Labour's tax plans has boosted
their support among voters.
The ICM poll for today's Guardian shows the Conservatives with a one-point
lead over Labour after a three-point rise to 42 per cent in its support
since December. Labour's support fell one point, while the Liberal Democrats
dropped from 14 per cent to 12 per cent. The poll was taken at the end of
last week.
The prime minister's statement that 'when it is prudent to make tax
reductions we will make them', was reinforced by a detailed exposition by Mr
Chris Patten, the party chairman, of the case for lower taxation.
Delivering the annual Disraeli Lecture in London, Mr Patten identified
taxation as the central difference between the two main parties. He added:
'Conservatives reduce taxes, whenever that is consistent with our
unshakeable commitment to sound money.'
Senior ministers stressed that the final judgment on the room for reductions
would not be made until much nearer the Budget.
Some of Mr Major's colleagues remain wary that charges of pre-election
bribery might undermine the Conservatives' claim to responsible economic
management. Mr Lamont will be anxious also not to risk upsetting confidence
on financial markets.
The ministers acknowledge, however, that Mr Major appears determined to
seize the opportunity of reducing income tax - either through raising
thresholds or by cutting the basic rate - if he can.
He reinforced that view in his first Commons clash of the new year with Mr
Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader. He rejected Mr Kinnock's claim that he had
ruled out as 'fool's gold' any pre-election tax cuts in an interview last
autumn.
Responding that he had been 'misquoted', Mr Major said the government would
cut taxes when it was prudent to do so because 'we believe that people are
better able to look after their own interest than any government, however
benevolent'.
Conservative party officials said plans were now in place to call the
election on either April 9 or May 7, following a Budget on March 3 or March
10.
They said that the broad themes of the election manifesto had been
established, with the focus on widening personal ownership and extending
personal choice. The Budget measures would be designed to underpin that
message.
Parliament, Page 10
Lex, Page 20
</TEXT>
