<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 92 / BCCI liquidation accelerates: High Court order opens
worldwide sale of assets to repay creditors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE WORLDWIDE liquidation of Bank of Credit and Commerce International
yesterday moved into full swing as the High Court in the UK issued a winding
up order against one of the group's two main operating arms.
That allows liquidators to begin the process of selling off the group's
assets and repaying creditors some of the Dollars 20bn owed.
The court order also triggers the UK's deposit protection scheme, by which
sterling depositors can claim 75 per cent of their deposits, up to a maximum
of Pounds 15,000.
A similar winding up order against the other substantial part of the group
was expected to be issued later in the day in the Cayman Islands.
It also emerged yesterday that BCCI's liquidators hope to conclude a
compensation deal with Abu Dhabi, the bank's majority shareholder, by the
end of this month. The deal is expected to involve the Gulf emirate in
paying the group's depositors between Dollars 3bn and Dollars 4bn. In
return, the liquidators would give up certain rights to sue third parties,
including Abu Dhabi itself.
The High Court in London issued a compulsory winding up order against BCCI
SA, the Luxembourg arm of the group which controlled the bank's branches in
various countries, including the UK.
Sir Donald Nicholls, the vice chancellor, said that the bank was 'plainly
and hopelessly insolvent'.
Earlier applications for a winding-up order, made by the Bank of England,
had been adjourned to allow time for the provisional liquidators, from
Touche Ross, to reach an agreement with Abu Dhabi about compensation. In
court yesterday, Mr Michael Crystal QC, counsel for Touche Ross, said that
the liquidators hoped to conclude a deal by the end of the month. Details
would be revealed when the terms are put to the court subsequently for
approval.
Yesterday's application, brought nearly two weeks after BCCI SA had been put
into liquidation in Luxembourg, was not opposed.
Hearings in the Cayman Islands and Scotland yesterday, and in the Isle of
Man today, had been arranged to coincide with the UK hearing, in order to
move the worldwide operations of BCCI into liquidation at the same time. The
liquidation of the Luxembourg-registered holding company is not expected
until April.
The High Court in London granted legal costs to the provisional liquidators,
the Bank of England, the depositors' group represented in court and former
employees of the bank, to be paid out of money recovered in the liquidation.
</TEXT>
