<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 92 / Core inflation rate continues to slide
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN'S core inflation rate fell further last month, reflecting sluggish
demand but supporting government hopes that upward pressure on prices will
continue to ease.
Figures from the Central Statistical Office show that in December the
year-on-year rate of increase in prices of goods at the factory gate - the
key measure of core inflation - was the lowest for 2 1/2 years.
In December, prices at the factory gate were only 5 per cent higher than in
December 1990, compared with a rise of 5.1 per cent in the 12 months to
November.
Although the figures provide little evidence of any immediate respite from
the economic gloom, the government believes lower inflation will provide the
platform for higher industrial investment and a recovery later this year.
The latest data suggest many manufacturers are continuing to cut prices to
maintain sales in a climate of fragile demand, while at the same time
benefiting from lower raw material and wage costs.
Stripping out volatile food, drink and tobacco prices, the output price
index rose by 3.8 per cent in the year to December - the lowest rate
recorded since February 1987 when the annual rise was also 3.8 per cent.
It compares with highs of 6.5 per cent in January and February last year.
Last month the cost of raw materials and fuel used by manufacturing industry
fell by a seasonally adjusted 0.7 per cent against the previous month, after
a 0.5 per cent rise in November. This left the price index of these
materials down by 1 per cent on the year compared with a 0.4 per cent annual
decline in November.
The fall in the cost of raw materials and fuel reflects the weak demand for
many types of commodities such as oil and metals. The price index for
petroleum products fell by 1.6 per cent on the year, while metals fell by
0.3 per cent.
Mr Gwyn Hacche, an economist at James Capel, said the fall in input prices
should encourage industry as pressures on profit margins eased.
The Treasury was heartened by the figures. It said they showed a continued
reduction in underlying inflationary pressures in the UK economy.
'The producer prices numbers should feed into lower underlying retail price
inflation in the months ahead,' a Treasury official said.
The Confederation of British Industry welcomed the figures as evidence that
the UK was 'genuinely achieving lower inflation than other European
Community countries'.
Household spending patterns Page 9
</TEXT>
