<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An extraordinary night for history. BBC2 begins a new series, The Day The
World Changed with Steven Berkoff making his choice: November 7 1938 when
Herschel Grynszpan shot a German diplomat in Paris. That was followed by
Kristallnacht which led eventually to the Holocaust (8.00).
Timewatch (8.10 BBC2) investigates 'the battle of the styles' in the 1830s
when classicists and modernists argued about the sort of building that
should replace the old Houses of Parliament which had burned down in 1834.
The argument scarcely differed from that which we hear today about the
design of public buildings.
ITV are wrapping their two-hour drama documentary The Treaty around 'News At
10', so this account of the emergence of the Irish Free State begins at 9.00
and ends at 11.45. BBC1 begins a 4-part series, Churchill, which claims to
be 'the first complete television biography of Britain's wartime leader'. It
is written and presented by Martin Gilbert who spent 25 years researching
and writing the 8-volume official biography. Today's programme covers
Churchill's early life and political career up to 1940 when he became Prime
Minister.
