FT  15 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Howard urges backing for
participation - Employment Questions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE companies were urged to encourage employee participation in management
on a voluntary basis by Mr Michael Howard, employment secretary, yesterday.
Insisting that voluntary arrangements were preferable to statutory
requirements, he described the best practice of British industry as 'second
to none'.
Mr Howard reaffirmed the government's determination to resist the imposition
of a 'statutory straitjacket' by the European Community.
He welcomed the part being played by the CBI in 'encouraging others to
follow the lead set by the best in industry'.
Mr Howard again attacked the Labour party's proposals for a statutory
minimum wage, claiming they would destroy 'countless jobs', particularly if
better-paid workers sought to maintain their differentials.
To Labour cheers, Mr Tony Blair, the shadow employment secretary, hit back
by calling on Mr Howard to accept that the recession was much deeper than
the government had so far been prepared to admit.
Mr Blair accused the government of cutting training provision at a time when
Britain had the fastest rising unemployment anywhere in Europe.
Mr Howard told Labour MPs that they were in no position to demand more
resources for training when it was not one of the priority areas for
increased expenditure authorised by Mrs Margaret Beckett, shadow chief
secretary to the Treasury.
