<HEADLINE>
FT  15 JAN 92 / Praise for Spanish minister who quit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SPAIN'S prime minister, Mr Felipe Gonzalez, was moving quickly yesterday to
resolve a delicate political crisis after his health minister, Mr Julian
Garcia Valverde, was forced to resign. Mr Gonzalez, to whom cabinet changes
are anathema, was understood to be preparing to name a successor.
Mr Garcia Valverde resigned because of a growing scandal surrounding land
speculation near Madrid by the state railway monopoly, Renfe, of which he
was president before being promoted to the government nearly a year ago. He
thus became the first minister in any of Mr Gonzalez's governments since the
Socialists first came to power in 1982 to resign as a direct result of
corruption charges, despite a string of political scandals.
El Pais, the country's biggest newspaper, yesterday welcomed the
resignation. 'In a country that seems to be getting used to a rigid division
between the reality of the lives of its citizens and their political
leaders, and in which the word resignation appears to have no place, Mr
Garcia Valverde's decision is highly significant,' it said.
By taking responsibility for a series of payments by Renfe to intermediaries
in order to buy land which it hoped to sell later to finance the
construction of a new railway line, Mr Garcia Valverde has overnight
converted himself into a minor folk hero. Last year alone the government was
caught up in at least four serious corruption scandals.
Mr Gonzalez, who is anxious to discard his government's shaky ethical image,
is understood to want to appoint a successor to Mr Garcia Valverde quickly
and is unlikely to use the resignation as an excuse for a large cabinet
reshuffle. But there are serious doubts about the health of his veteran
foreign minister, Mr Francisco Fernandez Ordonez, whom illness forced to
miss last month's Maastricht summit.
A rapid appointment to the health portfolio would help the prime minister
allay speculation that he might call a general election before he has to in
October 1993.
</TEXT>
