<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / London Stock Exchange: Futures lead an erratic equity sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TERRY BYLAND, UK Stock Market Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ECONOMIC and currency worries continued to overhang the UK stock market
yesterday and share prices again traced a sharply erratic pattern, often
directed by the trend of stock index futures. Although there was no lack of
specific features, trading volume overall slipped back from last week's
slightly improved levels.
The stock market was unsettled by the growing sounds of the political battle
building up ahead of this year's general election in the UK. The latest
statistics on domestic consumer credit, showing a dip in new credit and also
the fourth consecutive monthly fall in net credit, together with a very
modest increase in November's retail sales, appeared to undermine further
hopes that consumers will lead the UK economy out of recession still
overhanging the broad range of manufacturing companies.
Concern over the outlook for UK interest rates continued as the pound,
although calmer yesterday, softened further against the German D-Mark. Hints
of further strains among the home loan companies were no help to underlying
investment confidence in the equity sector.
The first day of the new equity account opened with share prices generally
lower in reaction to falls in stock prices in both Tokyo and New York.
London's setback was emphasised when an early premium on the FT-SE March
contract immediately brought in sellers, first of the future and then of the
underlying stocks.
A loss of 21 on the Footsie scale, however, was recovered as sterling
performed steadily and London picked up hints of a firmer opening on Wall
Street. The early setback in the Footsie was converted into a 13.7 points
gain. In the event, the Dow Average was a few points easier in UK hours but
the Footsie received further encouragement in late dealings from a renewed
rally in the futures market.
The final reading showed the FT-SE Index at 2,490.1 for a rise of 12.2 on
the day. At the session's best, the Footsie was still more than eight points
short of the 2,500 mark, and traders said there was not enough support
behind equities yesterday to give credence to this fresh move towards an
important chart hurdle.
Seaq volume slipped to 429.3m shares from Friday's 589.7m and dealers
believed that yesterday's total took in an increased proportion of
intra-market business. Customer, or retail, business increased at the end of
last week as some profits were taken.
Some disappointment was expressed yesterday that the new account had not
brought much sign of institutional buying.
Among the heavyweight blue chip stocks, bullish views on the US dollar kept
share prices firm. Oil shares staged a recovery as some UK securities firms
restored BP and Shell to their buying lists. But the UK financial sector
remained nervous, and modest losses were scattered across the leading names.
Pharmaceuticals, however, still seen as the most favoured sector for the
1990s, moved forward again, led by Glaxo.
The disappointing data on UK domestic credit made little impact on a retail
sector which had already failed to sustain its Christmas rally. Share prices
for the high street stores edged higher yesterday, but traders said this was
a technical rally rather than a change of stance by investors.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 36
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-14720</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CANA3AF9FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920114
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Markets Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE STOCK index futures sector finally boiled over yesterday, at least for a
while, and a hurried shrinking of the premium on the March FT-SE contract
brought some rapid footwork in the stock market by leading securities firms,
writes our markets staff.
The March contract opened firmly, showing a premium of about 26 points
compared with an estimated 22-point premium on fair value, the calculation
which allows for financing and dividend flows.
Sellers quickly appeared, as London traders noted the fall in Tokyo, and the
future came back smartly, driving the stock market down. By midsession the
March contract was close to fair value, and a few buyers appeared again.
This was the pattern for most of the session, until in the final minutes of
stock market trading the March contract advanced again, taking share prices
with it. Traders doubted whether the premium could avoid further selling
this morning.
In traded options, business was reduced and only 18,384 contracts traded,
compared with 24,779 on Friday. The FT-SE contract remained busy, however,
recording 4,832 deals against 4,988. British Airways topped the active
stocks list with 1,779 contracts traded.
</TEXT>
