<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / Money Markets: UK rates close level
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON LONDON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UK money rates were squeezed higher yesterday as sterling remained under
pressure on the foreign exchange markets, but closed little changed from
Friday, writes Simon London.
The Bank of England forecast a liquidity shortage of Pounds 1bn early in the
morning, later revised up to Pounds 1.1bn.
In early assistance, the Bank injected Pounds 456m funding, including a
Pounds 90m repurchase agreement maturing in equal portions on January 27 and
28 at 10 7/16 per cent.
In addition, the Bank purchased outright band 1 bank bills at 10 7/8 per
cent, band 3 bank bills at 10 3/16 per cent and band 4 bank bills at 10 1/8
per cent. In late morning a further Pounds 122m assistance was forthcoming,
comprising purchases of band 1, band 3 and band 4 bills at the same rates.
An afternoon liquidity injection comprising the purchase of Pounds 179m band
1 and band 3 bills was followed by Pounds 310m late assistance. This brought
total assistance for the day to Pounds 1.067bn, just short of the forecast
liquidity shortage.
The squeeze on liquidity during the day forced overnight unsecured money
rates up to 11 per cent in the afternoon session, from 10 3/4 - 1/2 per cent
at the close on Friday, before falling back to close at 10 3/4 - 5/8 per
cent.
The March short sterling futures contract on the London International
Financial Futures Exchange finished at 89.49.
In Frankfurt, call money interest rates were squeezed upwards as financial
institutions moved to build reserves ahead of a deadline for taxation
payments later this month. Overnight money traded at 9.45/55 per cent, from
the 9.40/50 per cent level which prevailed for most of last week.
Market participants commented that rates could be pushed higher still during
the middle of this week, although most expect call rates to remain below the
9.75 per cent Lombard rate, the Bundesbank's emergency funding rate for
financial institutions.
In Tokyo, the Bank of Japan recalled Y80bn loans from financial institutions
in the face of a forecast Y110bn liquidity surplus. In spite of this action,
overnight money rates declined to 5 3/8 per cent, from 5 1/2 per cent on
Friday.
Today, market conditions should be tighter. The Bank of Japan said it will
set a Y300bn auction-style repurchase pact for funds maturing on February
25.
</TEXT>
