<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / International Capital Markets: MoF considers licences move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPAN'S Ministry of Finance may grant investment trust management licences
to investment advisory companies, Reuter reports.
The idea is expected to be incorporated into the reform proposals made by
the Securities and Exchange Council, an advisory panel to the ministry. The
proposals will be submitted next month at the regular session of parliament.
The investment trust management business has been limited to securities
houses so far.
If investment advisory firms receive the licences, their holding companies
may gain an opportunity to enter the investment trust management field
through their subsidiaries.
However, sales of investment funds are seen as unlikely to be opened to
investment advisory companies, with brokerage houses continuing to
monopolise investment funds' sales by also marketing funds formed by
investment advisory firms.
</TEXT>
