<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / International Company News: Australian retailer may float
Woolworths chain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ADSTEAM, the Australian retailing and manufacturing group which is being
restructured by its banks, yesterday confirmed it is considering floating
its Woolworths supermarket chain after the completion of a ADollars 6bn
(USDollars 4.4bn) refinancing deal.
'A float of Woolworths is constantly under review. However, no decision has
been made on the timing of a float, and no decision is imminent,' said Mr
George Haines, the group's chief executive.
Analysts say Woolworths could raise between ADollars 1.5bn and ADollars 2bn
on the Australian stock exchange, which would make it Australia's second
highest capitalised retailer.
Woolworths is the main competitor to Coles Myer, Australia's largest
retailing chain. It has continued to perform strongly in spite of Adsteam's
financial problems.
Woolworths made pre-tax profits of ADollars 211m in the year to June, and is
expected to report profits of about ADollars 240m this year. Growth is
expected to slow over the next few years following the completion of an
investment programme.
Mr Haines said Adsteam was able to consider Woolworths' flotation 'in an
orderly manner' because of the completion of a refinancing deal for
Industrial Equity (IEL), the Adsteam affiliate which owns Woolworths. IEL,
jointly owned by three other Adsteam companies, has agreed credit lines of
ADollars 1.45bn with a syndicate of 14 banks which replaced its previous 51
lenders.
Adsteam said refinancing agreements for other companies in the group would
soon be completed, and would involve a cur in the number of participating
banks. Adsteam is said to have negotiated with about 80 banks.
The Adsteam group, formerly run by Mr John Spalvins, reported a consolidated
net loss of ADollars 1.57bn for the year to June, following interim losses
of ADollars 1.2bn. Adsteam's banks stepped in to restructure it in late
1990, after the shares came under selling pressure due to concern about the
group's cross-shareholding structure and extensive inter-company debt. Mr
Spalvins and two other directors were fired in December 1990.
</TEXT>
