<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / International Company News: A more primitive Citicorp after
shake-up at the top
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IT HAS BEEN a rough couple of years for Mr John Reed, the Citicorp chairman
who yesterday unveiled a senior-level management shake-up at the nation's
largest bank.
At the close of 1990, with real estate loan losses rising and Citicorp's
core capital-to-asset ratio slipping beneath the 4 per cent regulatory
minimum, Mr Reed began slashing the bank's dividend and workforce.
In October 1991, with Citicorp embarked upon a Dollars 1bn cost-cutting
plan, Mr Reed was again embarrassed - and Wall Street was severely
disappointed - when he revealed Dollars 1.6bn of loan write-offs, Dollars
885m of third-quarter losses, a radical revision of the cost-cutting plan
requiring an additional Dollars 700m of cuts in operating expenses and the
first halting of Citicorp's dividend in its 179-year history.
Now Mr Reed is to shuffle the bank's top management, moving to what he calls
'a much more primitive structure' to achieve better credit controls. He is
also acting to bring down costs as needed, to return to profits in the first
half of 1992 and to boost the bank's 3.6 per cent core capital ratio above 4
per cent by mid-1992.
Yesterday's management changes include the setting up of a series of
corporate task-forces that will deal with problem areas and seek to identify
asset disposals that will help strengthen capital.
Mr Reed says Citicorp's operating expenses are running at Dollars 10bn a
year, down from Dollars 10.7bn a year ago. His goal is annual costs of
Dollars 9bn by the end of 1992, to be achieved through further operational
cuts of Dollars 600m and sales proceeds of Dollars 400m.
The most visible changes, however, revolve around the ousting of Mr Michael
Callen, the head of Citicorp's US, European and Japanese corporate
businesses and the man who had responsibility for US real estate until Mr
Reed took personal charge of that portfolio last year.
Mr Callen, whose departure is termed a resignation, was a Reed loyalist. His
corporate division responsibilities will be taken up by Mr Onno Ruding, the
former Dutch finance minister who on January 21 will be named as a Citicorp
vice-chairman and board member.
Yesterday, Mr Reed was not shy about criticising the past management of the
corporate division, which suffered a Dollars 298m loss in the third quarter.
'One of the things I have been correctly criticised for is that the
management (of the corporate division) has produced some pretty horrendous
results. We are guilty of having run the business a bit cavalierly,' Mr Reed
said in an interview.
'When you run a corporate business that has the ability to destroy consumer
profits you are obviously running it with the wrong risk-reward ratio,' he
said, adding: 'I don't want a business to jeopardise the whole company.' He
noted that strengthening the corporate division's management was important
because this was 'not an area I myself have worked in'.
Turning to US commercial real estate, where Dollars 4.4bn, or 31 per cent,
of Citicorp loans are classified as non-performing, Mr Reed said he believed
that 'unusually high commercial real estate write-offs' would continue for
the next seven years.
He said he expected real estate write-offs, bad debt provisions and carrying
costs on foreclosed property to total Dollars 1.5bn to Dollars 2bn during
the next seven years, 'which for all practical purposes is forever'.
As for his own future, the subject of Wall Street speculation, Mr Reed was
brief: 'I will be in my position until I get the job done. I'm working my
tail off.'
</TEXT>
