<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / International Company News: Chase Manhattan falls to Dollars
135m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CHASE Manhattan, the New York money-centre bank, yesterday reported
fourth-quarter net income of Dollars 135m, down from Dollars 193m last year
when its figures were flattered by a Dollars 51m after-tax gain from the
sale of overseas real estate.
The results, which were broadly in line with market expectations, underlined
the efforts Chase has been making to cut its costs and the improved spreads
US banks have been enjoying between the cost of borrowing and lending money.
However, the figures also point up the continuing impact on bank profits of
the American property market slump.
Chase's net interest revenue during the fourth quarter rose from Dollars
839m last year to Dollars 868m, which, it said, reflected improved spreads
on interest-earning assets, partially offset by a higher average level of
non-performing assets and the effects of asset securitisation.
Its net interest margin - the difference between the average cost of
deposits and average yield on loans and other assets - was 3.95 per cent, up
from 3.66 per cent a year earlier.
However, the bank's provision for possible credit losses totalled Dollars
315m, up from Dollars 200m in the same period of last year and Dollars 265m
in the third quarter.
Excluding Third World debt, net write-offs in the quarter were Dollars 309m,
up from Dollars 240m last year. The increase included a Dollars 44m increase
in US commercial write-offs and Dollars 18m in US consumer write-offs.
The loan loss provision for the full year was Dollars 1.1bn, compared with
Dollars 1.3bn in 1990, and the bank warned that in view of the depressed
real estate market it was likely that 'the provision for possible credit
losses will continue at the relatively high level recorded in 1991'.
Fee and commission revenue totalled Dollars 436m, up from Dollars 417m a
year before, while revenues from trading jumped from Dollars 20m to Dollars
101m.
Other operating expenses totalled Dollars 986m, up from Dollars 960m in the
fourth quarter of 1990, due mainly to the takeover of a group of banks in
the state of Connecticut.
Mr James McDermott, an analyst at Keefe, Bruyette and Woods, commented:
'Their charge-offs are high but their expense control seems to be on track.'
Fourth-quarter net income per share totalled 80 cents, compared with 93
cents a year ago, excluding the benefits of the 1990 property disposals
which boosted the total to Dollars 1.32.
For the full year, the bank reported net income of Dollars 520m, or Dollars
3.12 a share, compared with a loss of Dollars 334m, or Dollars 3.31 a share,
in 1990.
</TEXT>
