FT  14 JAN 92 / French state groups to seek fresh capital
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By WILLIAM DAWKINS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AEROSPATIALE and Snecma, the French state-owned aircraft and jet engine
makers, yesterday revealed they were seeking substantial injections of
capital.
This provides the latest evidence of the financial pressures on the French
aerospace and defence industries, faced with falling orders from the
declines in air travel and arms budgets, plus heavy investment demands for
new products.
The gloomy background was reinforced yesterday by the DGA, the French state
weapons procurement agency, when Le Monde newspaper quoted DGA estimates
that the French arms business would lose up to 18,000 jobs this year.
Neither Aerospatiale nor Snecma gave exact details of their funding needs,
though officials indicated that Aerospatiale was negotiating to raise around
FFr1bn (Pounds 103m) by selling a minority equity stake to Credit Lyonnais,
the state-owned bank. Snecma has indicated in the past that its financing
needs this year will be FFr750m.
Mr Henri Martre, chairman of Aerospatiale, said he was negotiating for a
capital increase with a state-owned bank, while Mr Louis Gallois, chairman
of Snecma, warned that if the government could not provide the capital
needed, he would seek an alliance with a new private or public partner.
Aerospatiale revealed that new orders declined sharply last year to FFr28bn
 -14 per cent below forecast  - from FFr55bn in 1990, leaving total orders
at FFr100bn, or 2 1/2 years work.
