<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / The Lex Column: Aerospatiale
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Mme Cresson is doubtless still smarting from Brussels' decision to veto the
Franco-Italian takeover of de Havilland. But she has obviously not forgotten
that Sir Leon Brittan also gave his blessing to Credit Lyonnais'
participation in Usinor Sacilor, and is expected to approve BNP's FF1.25bn
capital injection for Air France. It is only natural to assume that
yesterday's confirmation of talks between Aerospatiale and an unidentified
French bank is the prelude to a similarly controversial deal.
With state owned engine-maker Snecma also renewing a request for outside
funds, pressures on the economie mixte look to be intensifying. In the
Snecma case private or foreign shareholders have not been ruled out. In the
state-owned insurance sector, rules restricting private shareholders to 25
per cent have been relaxed. But, as with airlines and steel, the solution
for the aerospace and defence group seems likely to involve an equity link
to a state-owned bank.
There are plenty of reasons why Aerospatiale requires fresh funds at this
stage: the impact of French defence cuts, the cash requirements of its
helicopter, regional aircraft and Airbus joint ventures, and the proposed
development of the A319 airliner. Given its pivotal position in European
alliances - and the speedier reaction this side of the Atlantic to changed
military circumstances - there may also be a commercial case for making such
an investment. The question is whether its new state-inspired partner will
be able to arrive at commercially sensible terms.
