<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Maxwell issue sets committee at
centre stage - The powers of parliament
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE future of parliament's select committee system has been thrown into the
balance as a consequence of the Maxwell brothers' refusal yesterday to
answer questions on the management of the Mirror Group's pension fund,
several MPs claimed last night.
If parliament does not now act decisively, some academics agree that the
backbenchers' committees - chiefly intended to act as a check on the
executive power of government - could suffer an irreversible diminution of
power.
But others - not least, in private, many government ministers  - are likely
to counter that the committees' powers have always been exaggerated and
centre specifically on a custom-and-practice, not legal rights, to question
the government.
Responding to the challenge yesterday, Mr Frank Field, the chairman of the
social security committee that had attempted to question the brothers, said
the issue must now be tackled by parliament itself.
'This has raised questions of crucial constitutional importance and I am
anxious they are dealt with in as non-controversial a way as possible,' he
said.
Nonetheless, while emphasising that the interests of parliament, the Mirror
Group pensioners and the Maxwells were all at stake, he added: 'The Maxwell
brothers in one stroke have brought two issues to a head: the lack of
ownership members have of pension funds and, second, what will happen to the
select committee system.'
The question of the Maxwell's right to stay silent in the face of
questioning by the committee will now go to the 'usual channels' - a
parliamentary euphemism for a behind the scenes negotiation between the two
main political parties.
Once a decision is taken, the committee will formally report the event by
publishing a report to the House. Many committee members of all parties
believe that the government and the Labour leadership can have little
alternative but to take some action or risk being seen as defending the
Maxwells' interests before those of parliament or aggrieved Mirror
pensioners.
They also pointed out that some questions asked yesterday did not raise any
suggestion that the brothers had been involved in alleged wrong-doing,
thereby rendering invalid the claim that they could prejudice any future
trial.
But what recourse does parliament have? The last time a citizen was fined
directly by parliament for contempt of its powers was as long ago as 1660
and the last custodial sentence was in 1880. Both decisions were of dubious
legality.
This century the last time punitive action was taken against a citizen was
in 1955 when Sir (then Mr) John Junor, a journalist, was called to the bar
of the Commons for an official reprimand for imputing that MPs were
receiving excess petrol rations.
What is more the modern select committee system has only been in force since
1980 when Mr Norman (now Lord) St John-Stevas overhauled it to allow MPs to
'shadow' government departments. Though this has raised a perception of
enhanced powers for backbenchers, hopes that they would become as powerful
as their US Congressional equivalents have been largely disappointed.
In reality, ministers have proved adept at stonewalling the committees when
they so desire. There are also no sanctions to force them to give evidence
or even to oblige them to attend. Furthermore, with (in most cases) a
government majority built-in to committee memberships, questioning can often
be tame.
As one former Cabinet minister noted contemptuously last month: 'A third of
a committee's members are young supporters of the government anxious for
office, a third are has-beens and a third are political opponents whose
criticisms can be dismissed.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
</PAGE>
