<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / Small business cites satisfaction as goal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE than nine out of 10 people running small businesses in Britain would
start up all over again in spite of the obstacles and relatively meagre
rewards, according to a survey published yesterday by Barclays Bank.
Independence rather than a desire for riches is the main incentive for
people setting up businesses, the survey adds.
The owners of such small businesses worked on average more than 60 hours a
week and earned only Pounds 6.67 an hour, compared with the average wage of
Pounds 7.30 an hour for a normal 40-hour week.
There are 400,000 more small businesses than a decade ago.
Of the 400 business owners questioned in the survey 68 per cent said they
found more satisfaction from being their own boss than from working for
somebody else. Although money was not the main motivation for run-ning their
own businesses, 32 per cent thought it would offer better financial
pros-pects.
A third said that when they worked for others they thought they could do
better than their employers or other businesses in the field. A further 31
per cent thought they could do as well as existing businesses. Nineteen per
cent had identified a gap in the market or developed a new product or
service.
The qualities that those questioned said were needed to succeed were hard
work, mentioned by 91 per cent, determination (89 per cent), pride (87 per
cent) and being good with people (76 per cent). The less highly rated
characteristics were intelligence (21 per cent), aggression (13 per cent)
and cunning (9 per cent). The single most important piece of advice offered
by people who had started up businesses was to 'research your market' (19
per cent) followed by 'get good advice' (18 per cent).
Women believed that they faced more difficulties than men in getting started
in business. Forty-five per cent said they were not taken seriously, while
40 per cent mentioned the additional burdens of family responsibilities, 26
per cent sex discrimination by suppliers or customers and 15 per cent
pressure to stay at home.
Starting Up. Market Research Enterprise. Paragon Communications. Tel 071-734
6030.
</TEXT>
