FT  14 JAN 92 / Treatment works to cost Pounds 350m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN HUNT, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NINE WATER companies are to invest a total of Pounds 350m in advanced water
treatment works to make their operations conform with the European Community
drinking water directive.
The nine cover 7 per cent of England's water supply and serve more than 4m
people. The UK government is at present before the European Court over its
failure to ensure that drinking water in parts of England meets the European
standard.
Yesterday Mr Michael Healey, chief inspector of the Drinking Water
Directorate, announced that Mr Michael Heseltine, environment secretary, had
approved undertakings from the nine companies. They provide for the best
available treatment technology to be installed at 32 treatment works to deal
with pesticide residues in drinking water.
Britain should have been conforming with the EC Drinking Water Directive by
1985.
Most of the improvements announced yesterday will be completed by 1995 but
four new plants will not be finished until 1996 and 1997.
The nine companies are: Severn Trent, Southern, East Surrey, North Surrey,
Tendring Hundred in Essex, Sutton in Surrey, and Eastbourne.
