<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Allowances to workers in London
increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALLOWANCES of more than Pounds 3,000 a year for staff working in central
London are now commonplace, according to a study.
The report by Incomes Data Services, the pay research group, found that two
thirds of employers increased allowances last year in spite of the
recession. There are, however, significant sectoral variations.
Three quarters of companies in retail and oil and chemicals increased their
allowances last year, but only about half the finance sector organisations
did so. Of the big four high street banks, all but one - National
Westminster - held their allowances at 1990 or earlier levels. The
government refused for the third year running to increase London allowances
for civil servants.
The study examined allowances paid by 170 organisations in London and the
south-east. Of those, 59 had inner-London allowances of Pounds 3,000 or
more, mostly in the finance sector.
About two thirds of building societies increased location allowances last
year. Alliance &amp; Leicester's service-related payments are the highest -
rising to a maximum of Pounds 4,440.
Among oil and chemicals companies, the highest allowance is paid by Imperial
Chemical Industries (Pounds 3,400).
In retailing, 16 of 21 organisations surveyed increased allowances last year
in spite of the recession. The highest allowances are reserved for stores in
the West End. Littlewoods pays Pounds 53.12 a week, BHS Pounds 64.20 and
Burtons Pounds 37.
Study 497. Incomes Data Services, 193 St John Street, London EC1V 4LS.
</TEXT>
