<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / James McCallum: Obituary
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
JAMES (Jim) McCallum, who died in hospital on Sunday at the age of 28, had
already established a reputation as a skilled and accurate FT reporter who
could get to the heart of complicated financial markets and explain them
with clarity and authority.
Educated at George Heriot's school in Edinburgh and at the London School of
Economics, he started in journalism in 1985 with the Financial Times World
Commodity Report. Brief spells there and at the shipping magazine Seatrade
led him to the Knight-Ridder financial news agency in 1986.
He had discovered the subject in which he was to specialise: the working of
the world's financial mar-kets.
In September 1989 he joined the FT's UK stock market reporting team and
quickly established a reputation with his colleagues and the markets. In the
2 1/2 years he worked for the paper he wrote on stock markets, stock index
futures, currencies and the money markets.
Those are not always the most intrinsically exciting of subjects but Jim
could explain why their daily movements were important and he could do so
with skill and authority.
His reports were required reading for those earning their living in these
markets. Senior figures in the City always found the time to talk to him and
his sharpness of mind and cheerfulness of disposition easily converted
contacts into friends.
He stood at the threshold of a wider career in journalism but his reputation
among his colleagues was already secure. His goodheartedness, genuine
affection and concern for his fellows was rooted in his active socialism, a
central feature of his character.
He suffered an aneurysm of the brain on New Year's Day and was immediately
admitted to St Bartholomew's Hospital, London.
He is survived by his parents, Mr and Mrs Ian McCallum of Edinburgh, and
their family.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
