<HEADLINE>
FT  14 JAN 92 / Government's home rescue schemes falter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN and DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE government's mortgage rescue schemes, announced in recent months to ease
the growing problem of house repossessions, have so far failed to get off
the ground, it emerged yesterday.
Mortgage lenders and housing associations are still reported to be at
loggerheads over the mortgages-to-rent scheme which formed the centrepiece
of the widely publicised package announced just before Christmas.
An earlier scheme to encourage lenders to make empty repossessed homes
available to the homeless through housing associations, announced at the
start of November, has also failed to make progress.
There appears to be little evidence that lenders have eased repossession
policies since the pre-Christmas package.
Some housing association executives at a seminar organised by the National
Federation of Housing Associations suggested that the government had acted
hastily in announcing its plan without finalising the details.
Under the scheme announced by the chancellor on December 19, the government
agreed to pay social security benefits designed to cover mortgage interest
direct to the lenders. In return, the lenders agreed to measures aimed at
helping homeowners in difficulties and at reducing repossessions by 40,000
this year.
These included a less aggressive approach to repossessing the houses of
people in arrears and a mortgage-to-rent scheme whereby housing associations
would buy homes about to be repossessed and rent them back to their former
owners.
To make the rents afford-able, the lenders said they would provide almost
Pounds 1bn of low-interest loans to the housing associations. The
associations say they need funds at rates as low as 5 per cent to enable
them to charge afford-able rents.
Housing associations - which were not consulted over the package  - have
been inundated with requests from homeowners in arrears seeking to join the
scheme.
But Mr Stephen Duckworth, head of housing finance at the NFHA, told the
seminar that only a 'limited number' of associations and lenders had even
begun negotiating terms for the loans.
One housing association executive said he felt that the lenders, having
achieved the direct payment of social security benefits, had now lost
interest in delivering their part of the bargain.
Another executive, Mr Bill Payne of the Yorkshire Metropolitan Housing
Association, said there was 'a chasm' between the interest rates housing
associations could afford to pay and the interest rates lenders wanted to
charge. 'I wonder whether it isn't all a political move to take the problem
off the agenda until after the general election,' he said.
Few lenders appear to have changed their policies since the government
announcement.
</TEXT>
